### Unit Tests in Rust

Unit tests verify individual functions and modules in isolation. They are placed alongside the code they test.

---

### Test Attributes

| Attribute | Purpose |
|-----------|---------|
| `#[test]` | Marks a function as a test |
| `#[should_panic]` | Test passes only if it panics |
| `#[should_panic(expected = "msg")]` | Panic must contain expected message |
| `#[ignore]` | Skip test by default |
| `#[cfg(test)]` | Only compile in test configuration |

---

### Assertion Macros

| Macro | Purpose |
|-------|---------|
| `assert!(expr)` | Assert expression is true |
| `assert_eq!(a, b)` | Assert a == b |
| `assert_ne!(a, b)` | Assert a != b |
| `debug_assert!(expr)` | Assert only in debug builds |

---

### Examples

```rust
#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn it_works() {
        assert_eq!(2 + 2, 4);
    }

    #[test]
    fn custom_failure() {
        let result = divide(10, 2);
        assert!(result.is_ok(), "Division failed: {:?}", result);
    }

    #[test]
    #[should_panic(expected = "divide by zero")]
    fn test_divide_by_zero() {
        divide(10, 0);
    }

    #[test]
    #[ignore = "expensive computation"]
    fn expensive_test() {
        // long running test
    }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Unit tests use the `#[cfg(test)]` module attribute so they are compiled only during testing. Use `#[should_panic]` for testing error conditions. Use `#[ignore]` for tests that are expensive or currently failing.

